n by proposing an integrated approach to the study of bilingualism in minority and majority settings. Programmes for indigenous groups, for national minorities and for migrants are analysed together with programmes aimed at dominant language groups, by well-known scholars from eight different countries in Europe and the Americas. Each contribution seeks to go beyond the traditional dichotomy between policy, practice and research into bilingual education programmes for majority language speakers, and modalities offered for minority language speakers. Thus, the book argues for the construction of a shared discourse for research into bilingualism and bilingual education and for the adoption of an ecological perspective on language education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation, BilingualvCross-cultural studies. 0aEducation, BilingualxCross-cultural studies. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxCross-cultural studiesxEducation. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxEducationvCross-cultural studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  abilingual education.  alanguage education.  aminority languages.  amultilingualism.1 aAnderson, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanfi, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Ofelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Eve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamel, Rainer Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHélot, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHélot, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKenner, Charmian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaoire, M